initial_story: in recent years, classical convolutional neural networks (cnns) have beenapplied for image recognition successfully. quantum convolutional neuralnetworks (qcnns) are proposed as a novel generalization to cnns by usingquantum mechanisms. the quantum mechanisms lead to an efficient trainingprocess in qcnns by reducing the size of input from $n$ to $log_2n$. this paperimplements and compares both cnns and qcnns by testing losses and predictionaccuracy on three commonly used datasets. the datasets include the mnisthand-written digits, fashion mnist and cat/dog face images. additionally, dataaugmentation (da), a technique commonly used in cnns to improve the performanceof classification by generating similar images based on original inputs, isalso implemented in qcnns. surprisingly, the results showed that dataaugmentation didn't improve qcnns performance. the reasons and logic behindthis result are discussed, hoping to expand our understanding of quantummachine learning theory.
stories: In recent years, the field of language processing has witnessed significant breakthroughs, particularly in the realm of transformer-based models. However, traditional recurrent neural networks (RNNs) continue to be plagued by vanishing gradients, hindering their performance. Inspired by the principles of quantum computing, quantum recurrent neural networks (QRNNs) have been proposed as a novel generalization of RNNs, leveraging quantum mechanisms to improve their training process. This paper presents an implementation and comparison of both traditional RNNs and QRNNs, testing their losses and prediction accuracy on three benchmark datasets: WikiText, Penn Treebank, and IWSLT. Furthermore, we explore the application of linguistic regularization, a technique often used in traditional RNNs to reduce overfitting, in QRNNs. Counterintuitively, our results indicate that linguistic regularization actually impeded the performance of QRNNs. The underlying reasons and implications of this finding are analyzed, aiming to expand our understanding of quantum machine learning theory.

In the realm of generative art, a new wave of creative breakthroughs has emerged, driven by advancements in neural style transfer. Inspired by the principles of fractal geometry, fractal neural networks (FNNs) have been proposed as a novel generalization of traditional neural networks, leveraging self-similar patterns to improve their representational capabilities. This paper presents an implementation and comparison of both traditional neural networks and FNNs, testing their performance and creative outputs on three benchmark datasets: Cityscapes, Places, and LSUN Bedroom. Furthermore, we explore the application of aesthetic regularization, a technique often used in traditional art to guide composition, in FNNs. Unexpectedly, our results indicate that aesthetic regularization actually enhanced the aesthetic value of FNN-generated artworks. The underlying reasons and implications of this finding are analyzed, aiming to expand our understanding of generative art theory and the intersection of art and machine learning.
